summary_markdown: This table outlines perceived attributes and outcomes associated with garments, categorized by "Garment attributes" and "Quality garment." Under "Garment attributes," several concepts are presented, including "Coordinated," "Expense," "Sexy," "Attractive to others," "Self-confidence," and "Achievement." These are further elaborated with related concepts such as "Aggravation," "Acceptance by others," and "Project self-image." The "Quality garment" section introduces "Physical imprisonment," "Physical comfort," "Obligatory wearing," "Emotional freedom" (crossed out), "Happy," and "Elegant." Additional related concepts in this section include "Concern," "Emotionally comfortable," "Variety of design," "Feel thin," and "Physical control," alongside "Anger." The structure appears to be a comparative or associative mapping of garment characteristics to psychological and social outcomes.
